segments.text: On the bed making, when you were a fish, you had to make somebody else's bed on a regular basis?
No, normally not.
What about when you were an upperclassman?
Did you have a fish make your bed?
No, we usually made our own.
I was curious, some of the people... You'd get some fish in there to help us clean up.
Some of the people indicated that when they were a fish, they had to make the bed.
Well, they did.
Some of those boys did.
I don't think we ever did bother about it a great deal.
Did you have any favorite instructors while you were there?
Oh, yeah, we had some nice people.
We had a lot of them that I don't remember.
A fellow named Jim, Slim Jim Hayden, I think, was a biology professor.
Everybody liked him.
Yes, Sabine Paul.
Everybody liked him.
And old Duke Thornton was a chemical department, chemistry department prof. Everybody liked old Duke.
He's still living in College Station.
You don't mean it.
Is that right?
Yeah.
My associate interviewed him a couple weeks ago.
Is that right?
Yeah, I knew him well.
And pretty smart cookie, too, that chemistry.
And animal husbandry department, there was a fellow named Burke, was a nice fellow.
Bell, who later went, was hard-boiled, later went to Kansas.
Made an outstanding name for himself in Kansas.
Animal husbandry department, a fellow named Templeton.
All under my own brother, see, who was head of the department at that time, so.
And, uh...
The other, I've forgotten.
Did you ever have any classes under Dr. Mark Francis?
Oh, yeah.
Dr. Francis was something else.
You bet.
No, thank you.
And Marsteller, I had a class under Dr. Francis.
Marsteller, well, yeah.
They were exceptional men, no doubt about it.
I had gathered from what people told me that Dr. Francis was really something else.
Oh, he was.
He was a good storyteller.
Oh, he was a good storyteller, and he was smart.
Morstella was a fine man.
He was very capable.
Yeah, I enjoyed my vet work.
I enjoyed my vet classes.
I've forgotten, Lord, who all was it.
You know, you forget those things of who the men were.
I believe when you first went there, Milner was president.
He resigned and Bazell came in.
Well, Perea was made president pro tem.
Perea was acting pro tem for a while.
That's right.
They saw the best part of Catfish Miller.
How'd he get the name Catfish?
God, I don't know.
He had it when you got there.
Yeah.
And then Brazell came there.
Because Brazell had a hard time changing his thinking from CIA down to A&M College.
They made it pretty rough on him.
The cadets did, you mean?
You bet.
They made it pretty hard on him.
I can remember one instance that he was walking down the walk in front of Milner Hall and all of a sudden this water come tumbling down.
Wasn't right, but it was funny.
Did they come to respect him though before the... Oh yeah, Milner was a, he was a good
good educator.
I mean, Brazell was a good educator.
Yes, he did a lot of A&M College.
Had a nice family.
Yeah, Brazell was all right.
He just had a hard time fitting in down there because that dang school at that time was a little bit rough and ready, you know.
A little bit different from girls' school.
What about the commandant?
You mentioned that Levi G. Brown is commandant.
Well, he was replaced by a fellow named James R. Hill.
And he wasn't as tough.
Hill was a nice fella, but he wasn't hard-boiled as old Levi Brown.
Levi Brown came out as, what, 7th Cavalry or 5th Cavalry?
He was tough as a boot.
But he made things run.
Yeah.
like they ought to be run, see.
And he had some good sergeants under him there, see.
They had some Army sergeants, retired Army sergeants there.
There was old Sergeant Kenyon, Sergeant Smart, Sergeant Highland.
And those boys all respected those boys.
They got along.
They knew people, see.
Now what did the sergeants do?
Did they teach military tactics of that nature?
Well, they worked in the Commandant's office.
and took care of a lot of the detail.
And they'd make a periodical inspection of those dormitories and were around the campus all the time.
Some fine men, real fine.
All three of those fellows, everybody loved them and highly respected.
When Hill came there, Hill was,
I don't, I believe he was a lieutenant in the Army when they sent him in.
He could have, not over a first, could have been second lieutenant.
But old Levi G. Brown, he was some man, he was something else.
You'd have to respect Levi Brown, although he was tough as a boot.
The boys respected him.
He covered all the ground he stood on.
And although he put me in the bugle corps, I never did dislike him first.
It was a lot of fun.
Well, that didn't really hurt you going in the biblical court.
No, it didn't hurt me.
You didn't have to learn how to play.
I didn't have to carry that gun.
Did the cadets who were officers in the Corps have any special privileges as opposed to other cadets now?
Earlier you said something about the senior privates could skip out on drills and things like that.
Oh, well, the senior private had more fun than anybody because he didn't have to go to any formation.

Of course, the senior officers had privileges that nobody else had in a way that they could get off and they could get furloughs and they could go to town and they could stay out after taps and those kind of things.
Other than that, I was not aware of it because I was the buck private and I knew it.
There wasn't much I could do about it.
For a long time, a lot of the students who have gone to Texas A&M have had jobs of one sort or another.
Did you have a job of any kind?
No, I didn't.
No, I was very fortunate that I didn't have to work my way through school.
Now, Ron Stangle did work his way through school under my brother.
First time I ever saw Ron Stangle, he was riding a 2,200-pound purchasing stallion.
And, of course, short legs, and his legs sticking right straight out.
I'll never forget.
I've told it on him.
It'll take many years later.
Let's see.
You graduated then in 16.
Skip over a couple of years up to the time of the First World War.
Did you have any role in that?
No, I did not.
I was in the cattle business, unfortunately, about spring of 1917.
Really in 1917, just in time to get in the drought and was tied up with a bunch of cattle and impossible for me to go at that time.
Later on I did go down to San Antonio and volunteered for the regular army.
They sent me to Houston for examination and had us all build a whole bunch of us out at Rice Institute for physical.
We were all built to go up to Louisville, Kentucky for artillery camp.
The war was over before we ever got transferred up there.
I went out to Fort Sam Houston, went to San Antonio and volunteered for regular Army.
And the old colonel out there said, well, Mr. Burns, if you had an education, I told him, yeah, four years in A&M College.
He said, you mean tell me you came out here to volunteer as a bug driver?
I said, I'd just as soon be private as a colonel.
The way it was to me.
He said, well, I'm not going to take you.
He said, I do want you to go over to Houston.
I'm going to send you over to Houston.
I want you to go over there and take an examination for artillery.
So that's what I did.
One of the things that I find of some interest, skipping back to your time on campus,
You obviously weren't particularly excited about the military, but yet you got into the Ross Volunteers.
Oh, yeah, yeah.
Ross Volunteers was an honorary company, and it was a precision drill deal.
We enjoyed it, you bet.
Well, that was pretty much an honor, I take it, to be elected.
That's right, you bet.
It was really an honor military company is what it was.
That's what I would consider it, yes.
You were also on a couple of stock judging teams.
Yeah, I was a member of the junior and senior stock judging team.
How were you selected to be on the team?
Well, for the proficiency and grades, evidently.
This was not a separate organization in a sense.
You were an animal husbandry and judging animals was part of your curriculum.
We made a lot of trips in our junior year, Fort Worth, Oklahoma City, around.
We were supposed to go to Chicago our senior year, but had foot and mouth disease, so we didn't get to make trips.
I believe the same thing happened to Mr. Stangle.
He didn't get to go to Chicago because of the same.
Yeah, I think that's probably right.
But he coached a team that won up there, I think.
Yeah, I believe he would have been on the junior team when you were a senior.
Yeah, that's right.
You missed out on that.
Now, you said after you graduated, you went into the livestock business.
Yeah, the cattle business in West Texas.
It hasn't been time to get caught in a bad drought of 1917 and 1918.
I got a very liberal education in the cattle business.
A very costly one.
Very costly one.
What finally developed with that?
Well, of course, I got heavily involved financially and shipped cattle into New Mexico and into the Panhandle.
Finally had to sell out.
It took a long time to pay out.
I believe you had something called the Burns Livestock Company.
Yeah, that's right.
And what, M-I-C-H-E-S, how you pronounce it?
Yeah, it was down in Dawson, Borden County.
We later sold that ranch.
There were several of us interested in a family interest.
We sold that ranch in 1929.
I went to work for Texas National Cotton Seed Products Association, A.L.
Ward, in the educational service.
He was an A&M man, too, wasn't he?
Yeah, 1910 man.
Mm-hmm.
As a field man for them, and I traveled everything from Pennsylvania, Pacific Coast, Rio Grande River to Canada about six, seven years.
And a real good education.
And I contacted all the livestock people, the cattle people, the feedlot people, the sheep people, the experimental station people.
I had made a very wide acquaintance during those years.
This was what, in trying to develop a market for cottonseed products?
A market for cottonseed products, that's right.
That was a promotion deal and then sponsored by the Texas Cottonseed Crushers Association and the National Cottonseed Products Association.
And purely a promotional deal, educational deal, educate the public how to use cottonseed products to the best advantage.
And also to follow the experimental work that was going on at all the colleges and universities.
Experiment station.
And of course promoting the sale of cottonseed products to the
large feeders, little ones and large ones too.
Of course, the feedlot business was not like it is today with these big feedlots to the southwest.
Primarily, all your beef cattle were fed in the corn belt.
You shipped them up there and then shipped the meat back.
Whereas today, you've got an entirely different setup.
What would you describe as the setup today?
I mean, there's still some cattle shipped to the corn belt.
Oh, yes, they feed some cattle up there, but they've largely gone into a production deal up there, and a lot of farmers don't feed any cattle anymore.
They sell the corn.

There are a lot of cattle fed in Ohio and Indiana and Ohio and Nebraska and Pennsylvania, but the big feedlots, the big volume of fed cattle today is in the southwest, the Great Plains area, the panhandle in eastern New Mexico, western Oklahoma, southwestern Kansas, eastern Colorado.
primary feed then?
Grain sorghum production is largely responsible for it and the fact that they saved the freight on a lot of these cattle going to Corn Belt.
A close source of grain and a close source of protein, your cotton seed products.
Cotton seed products with protein.
Probably has been overdone.
I'm afraid it has been.
It looks like a lot of these boys are in trouble, bad trouble.
Producing too much beef, you mean?
No, too many feedlots.
Competition got pretty keen for feeder cattle.
Bought some of them too high, and then they had the freeze on beef last year, which was so uncalled for.
Let it alone worked itself out.
Then you had your boycotts, and then you had your truck and strike.
Everything that worked against orderly marketing.
Well, the freeze on the price of the beef and the failure to freeze the cost of the feed was really the disastrous part of it.
That's right.
And then, of course, since that time, well, cattle prices of beef have gone way down.
People held a lot of cattle that shouldn't have been held.
It should have continued to market because you get over finished cattle on the market and they've been a drug on the market ever since.
Just now begin to get out from under them.
The tremendous amount of grain that was exported ran the grain feed price way up.
There's no doubt about that.
I'm pretty optimistic about the fat cattle price, but I'm not very optimistic about the cattle business generally for the next few years.
But you think this is going to be a cycle that it'll level out ultimately?
It always has.
Yeah?
Yeah.
So there's every reason to believe that it will again.
It's not new, you know.
No, no.
I've seen several of these wrecks.
Yeah.
Well, I know that...

My grandfather in Lee County was involved in the cattle business for a long time, and since his death, my grandmother and my father have been involved, and the price has gone up and down and up and down.
Those people who, when the price goes up and they buy a few cattle and are going to make a killing, and then the price drops and they have to sell less than they bought, they lose their shirt.
That's right.
I've seen all of it happen.
Stay in it.
Why?
lose sometimes and win sometimes, but overall I guess they do fairly well.
You were with the Pitchfork Land and Cattle Company for a good long while.
Were you involved in part ownership of that?
Well, I was a stockholder in it.
Later made a direct of the company.
I stayed with the Cotton Seed Products Association until about 1934 or 1935.
For a short time I was associated with Trader's Oil Mill at Fort Worth.
Later with Anderson Clayton as acting sales manager for 11 oil mills that they owned in West Texas.
Western Cotton, they called it West Texas Cotton Oil Company at that time, Abilene.
So they moved me to Abilene, made me acting sales manager down there.
And I stayed there several years.
uh, moved me to San Angelo about 1940.
The West Texas Cotton Oil Company was a subsidiary of Anderson Clayton.
That's right.
Uh, during the years I was at Abilene, I was principally in sales organization.
I was sales manager, handle the sales for the group of mills that Anderson Clayton owned.
Uh,
In 1942, I went to Pitchfork Land and Cattle Company at Guthrie with own rights of approximately 120,000 acres in King and Dickens County, 85 miles east of Lubbock.
As manager there and stayed with those people 23 years.
I'm still associated with them, still on their board of directors.
In 1947, we bought 43,000 acres of country for the first part of the Matador Land Cattle Company that was cut up, which had joined us.
In 1952, we bought 50 sections of country in Wyoming and Laramie and Albany County, Laramie, Wyoming, which we still operate.
And I retired at the age of 70 in 1965.
Although, as I said, I do remain on the board and still act in an advisory capacity and handle their real estate and some oil leases and stuff for the company.
So the company owns land and operates them as ranches, but also has oil leases?
No, no.
They've leased a lot of it, but they don't have any oil.
Uh-huh.
Have they leased other people's lands?
No, no.
I have leased out two different oil companies who've drilled wells over there, see.
I've handled those leases.
But they haven't hit any oil yet?
No, just haven't been lucky enough, that's all.
But when you were manager,
Did you have control over both the Texas and the Yes, I was general manager, executive manager of the company.
So you had both Control, all of it was cleared through me.
So you had both the Texas and the Wyoming property.
Yes.
And that was quite a chunk of land.
Well, we had between 100 and 90 and 200,000 acres of country.
And how many head of cattle did you have?
Well, it varied, of course.
weather condition, market conditions, but from 8 to 10,000 cattle most years.
Did you run both range cattle and a feedlot operation?
No, no, we did not.
We fed some cattle during that time, but largely a production proposition, range cattle production, and maintained a registered herd of
cattle for replacement bulls.
So you would just keep the calves up until the time they would be ready to go to a feedlot?
Well, the reason we bought the Wyoming ranch is that we had been selling light yearlings in the spring and
We figured it would be more profitable to carry these light cattle and get a cheap summer gain on them and sell them in the fall.
That's the reason we bought the Wyoming rights.
And we still maintain it.
And we still send some cattle up there.
It's been years.
It has been more advantageous to us to sell these cattle.
or maybe precondition them and put them in the feedlot down here rather than to go to Wyoming with them.
In those years, we bought outside cattle and light yearlings in the fall, wintered them, and summered them and made two-year-old cattle out of them.
Really a thing that we're still doing.
So your operation is influenced a good bit by the market conditions, the weather conditions?
Range conditions, and it's flexible.
That's right.
As it would have to be if you wanted to stay in business.
Yeah, that's right.
That's right.
Yeah.
Mr. Barnes and I lived over at the ranch 23 years.
Where are you living now?
I live out here on 19th Street.
And we bought a home here in 1963.
And the day they shot Kennedy.
And we remodeled it and redecorated it and air conditioned it.
Moved up here in 65 when we left the ranch.
So you haven't lived on the ranch then for about nine years.
But you still keep a pretty close tie to it.
Yeah, down there pretty often.
Except for the young man who succeeded me as manager.
He came to me in 1948 and he's still there.
Okay.
Okay.
I made a reference a few minutes ago to an old fellow who was with the military department of A&M College for many years named Sergeant Kenny.
Sergeant Kenny was a big, fat fellow, and everybody loved him.
Sort of gruff, but a fine character.
During my junior year in the spring, we used to have a few keg rolling.
That was before brown went dry.
So we had a few keg rollers and get some negro boy to bring us a keg of beer.
I can remember one April, a whole bunch of us got a keg of beer brought out to the old Experiment Station up on the hill between Brown and College.
And we were having a beer party, and there were several on the campus in the surrounding area.
But anyhow, Dr. Brazell and a commandant, Lieutenant Hill, came down the road and saw us.
And of course the car came and the boys ran off in a cotton patch on one side of the road, some of them on the other side.
So they went up to where they could turn around and came back.
They went back to the campus and instigated a midnight inspection and caught a lot of boys absent.
Some of them had gone to the latrine, some of them were sleeping on the roof, so they'd say it.
And some of them were just gone.
Well, there's a big hullabaloo, and they sent out a request that you were absent.
So and so, midnight inspection, please report to the Commandant's Office explanation.
Well, wherefore so?
Well, you're absent.
Well, some of us had permits to be in bronze, some of them, as I said, sleeping on the roof, and some of them going to the train one time.
But one young fellow, who Sergeant Kenny had up before him, and he lived in San Angelo, and I believe he was a freshman.
And with us were several juniors, I think it was my junior year.
And I think both, one or two juniors, I believe both of them are gone now.
One was a very dear friend of mine.
He and I went through a lot of things up and down this day in M College.
This young man from St. Angelo, and I think he's still living.
Sergeant Kennedy asked him, says, where were you last night at 12 o'clock midnight?
It may have been midnight.
It may have been 11, I don't know.
He says, I was eating strawberries.
He says, eating strawberries at that time?
Yes.
I said, get them while the dew's on them.
It's all good.
Old Sergeant Kenny says, young man, that's the biggest lie I've ever heard.
All my years, that's the biggest lie I've ever heard.
You can go.
Let me ask you a question about something that's just occurred to me.
There was a period of years, and I believe this may have been while you were there, that
In the spring of the year, the cadets kind of went on an extended hike onto the Brazos River.
Oh, yes, yes, I made several of those, you bet.
You walk down, walk back, and carry that gun with you.
And a bedroll, too, huh?
That's right.
How long did you stay there when you went?
I reckon I stayed all night.
I don't know.
I've forgotten.
I remember walking down there, camping down there.
What did you do when you got there?
Oh, they had target practice down there, platoon practice, and extended order drill, some stuff like that.
Someone once said that it was to keep you out of mischief on April Fool's Day.
Oh, yeah, yeah, that's right.
That's the reason it was originated, I understand.
It's a pretty good long hike down there.
Yeah, I got, well, if you follow the road to the,
To the Jones River Bridge, it's nine miles.
That's right.
It was nine miles then, too.
That's right.
I still have some old pictures that were taken on that hike.
That's right.
We have a few pictures in the archives of some of those hikes, and we have one big long one.
It must be about three and a half feet long.
It's kind of a panoramic view of the encampment.
I believe that was in 1910 or 11, something like that.
Yeah, yeah.
Well, these pictures taken, I forgot what year, what spring, but I still have some of them.
There's very few of my classmates still living.
Most of them are gone.
Yeah, I can imagine, too.
I have one very dear friend who lives in Greenville, South Carolina, that I hear from very often.
Most of my other close companions are gone.
I have one very dear friend who lives in Dallas.
I believe he told me the other day when I called him as I came through Dallas from St. Louis that he was 80, I believe he told me 81, 82.
He says I walk a mile every day.
He's in pretty good health.
Yeah, must be to do that.
